Dreadful service by Cumberland Building Society
I wished to open a One Year Fixed Rate savings account with the Cumberland. I was encouraged to use the telephone option as a first step, and the agent took me through the preliminary mandatory form that has to be agreed before I and my wife sign the agreement. It was agreed that my wife and I would go to the Kendal branch to sign the following day: we did on Friday 19th Sept at 1130hrs, signed the form, and asked how the money would be paid into the new Fixed Term account. Using Internet Banking, I was told that the branch would send me an account number by email that I should enter on the website, and this would be done probably that day. By Monday morning, 22nd Sept, I had heard nothing from the Cumberland, so I phoned the Carlisle number. The adviser told me that he would look into the matter and contact me: that never happened.  On Tuesday 23rd, I again phoned the Cumberland to be told, again, that the adviser would look into the matter. I tried again on the Tuesday afternoon and spoke to Heidi Martin (I think). She told me that she would email, giving me the new account number and sort code, and if I entered this on the webpage describing my account with the Cumberland, I could open the new account and transfer the money into it. I opened my account page on-line, selected pay someone new, entered my and my wife's initials and name and the account number, entered the amount to be paid in, only to be told in red that the account name was NOT recognised and that only cash amounts LES THAN £10,000 could be entered into the account which was not the agreement we had signed up for. So, at 1645hrs on the Tuesday, I phone the Cumberland again and this time a male adviser talked to me. He explained that once I had entered any amount lass than £10,000 into the new account and it had been accepted, I could then enter the full amount into the new Fixed rate account. Because it wa now after 1700hrs, and it had been 48 hours of frustration on my behalf, he would do the transaction for me. He did, I checked that all was as it should be using the Cumberland webpage for Internet banking, and it was correct. 
I have so many issues with the service the Cumberland gave me when opening this account:
a) that the Kendal branch failed to keep me informed and failed to send me details of the new account number;
b) that nobody described the precise details that I should follow to open the new account and transfer money into it. Customers like me open new Fixed Rate Savings Accounts very infrequently, so have no idea how the Cumberland system works. With other banks I deal with, opening new Savings Accounts are easy, completed on-line - with all the security checks in-place to comply with current legislation;
c) except for the last adviser I consulted, nobody offered to talk me through the procedure for opening a new Account and transferring money with my Cumberland account on the screen of my 'desk top': that would have saved everybody time;
d) the Cumberland closes down the webpage containing my account details after a relatively short period of time. This happened twice during the afternoon of the 23rd, once when being helped by your adviser. This does not occur with other banks: once I have opened my account using Internet Banking, they give me plenty of time to search the website, get the information I want, and act accordingly. 
e) every time I wish to enter the Cumberland website  and open up my account, I have to phone a number for the Cumberland to respond, giving me a reference number to enable me to enter my own account page. No other bank does this: I entered details unique to me, that stay the same over time, and I get into my accounts no problem. Technology has moved on, making it simpler to use Internet Banking using a desktop computer: the Cumberland has made using an app. on a phone easy to use, so why is it so difficult to use a desktop computer?
The consequences of my difficulties opening a new Savings Account might appear trivial to the Cumberland. For me, I have lost three days of interest at around 4% on my money which was held by the Cumberland in my ordinary account: I have wasted two entire days trying to get the account set up; now, I wish I had never bothered to try and complete this financial contract on-line; I live 13 miles from Kendal and catch a bus to visit the Kendal branch, which would have meant my wife and I spending two entire days travelling to the branch and back to sign a form and then open the account itself at the branch; then there is the frustration that nobody in the Cumberland acts on behalf of the customer - except for the last adviser I spoke to on the 23rd.
